Sign up for email alerts for Gibraltar travel advice
On 22 March 2020 the Government of Gibraltar announced a social lock down in Gibraltar to slow the spread of COVID-19. People will be allowed to leave their homes only for essential work, to shop for essentials and for brief exercise. Full details of the restrictions which came into effect at 12am on Tuesday 24 March 2020 can be found in the Chief Minister’s statement in the Government of Gibraltar Press Release
Most visits to Gibraltar are trouble-free. Violence and street crime are rare. See Crime
Following the recent announcement that British Airways will continue flights to and from Gibraltar on a reduced schedule, the Government of Gibraltar (GoG) has issued important new guidance for passengers wishing to use these flights. Please note that this applies to both those passengers wishing to enter Gibraltar from Spain to return to UK on these flights and also to those wishing to enter Spain from Gibraltar. The guidance can be found in this GoG Press Release.
Gibraltar is a British Overseas Territory. There’s no formal British consular representation in Gibraltar and the local authorities deal with all requests for consular assistance. See Consular assistance
The Government of Gibraltar has issued some press releases with guidance on Brexit.
In response to the coronavirus (COVID-19) pandemic there are border restrictions are in place. See Crossing between Spain and Gibraltar
You must hold a valid passport to enter Gibraltar. See Passport validity
Gibraltar is not part of the EU Common Customs Territory. The amount of goods (e.g. tobacco and alcohol) that you can take into and out of Gibraltar is more limited than for visits between the UK and other EU countries. See Customs
Terrorist attacks in Gibraltar can’t be ruled out. See Terrorism
If you need to contact the emergency services call 199 (police) or 190 (ambulance and fire).
Take out comprehensive travel and medical insurance before you travel.
